<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="184" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,873,1438]" pageId="1" pageNumber="184">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1053,1078]" pageId="1" pageNumber="184">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[473,688,1053,1078]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Singilis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="184" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shavrini" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[473,495,1054,1077]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="184">S.</emphasis>
(s.str.) 
<emphasis box="[596,688,1053,1077]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="184">shavrini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[703,775,1053,1078]" pageId="1" pageNumber="184">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[703,775,1053,1078]" pageId="1" pageNumber="184" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, in body shape, elongate elytra, and extremely dense punctuation of head and pronotum, but can be easily distinguished by uniformly dark brown body. Length 
<quantity box="[1337,1433,1089,1114]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="184" unit="mm" value="6.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="6.0">6–7 mm</quantity>
. Body usually uniformly dark brown (
<figureCitation box="[587,656,1125,1150]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1778,1801]" captionTargetBox="[161,1413,210,1726]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,195,1755]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Habitus of Singilis (s. str.): 1 — S. allardi (Basilewsky, 1963) (Zambia); 2 — S. allardi, Paratype (immature); 3 — S. shavrini sp. n., Paratype; 4 — S. ambulans (Peringuey, 1896); 5 — S. cribricollis (Peringuey, 1904) (Salisbury, RSA); 6 — S. cribricollis, Lectotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/265437/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="184">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), immature specimens with visible triangular elytral band (
<figureCitation box="[1350,1423,1125,1150]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1778,1801]" captionTargetBox="[161,1413,210,1726]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,195,1755]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Habitus of Singilis (s. str.): 1 — S. allardi (Basilewsky, 1963) (Zambia); 2 — S. allardi, Paratype (immature); 3 — S. shavrini sp. n., Paratype; 4 — S. ambulans (Peringuey, 1896); 5 — S. cribricollis (Peringuey, 1904) (Salisbury, RSA); 6 — S. cribricollis, Lectotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/265437/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="184">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Head and pronotum with strong, almost isodiametric microsculpture throughout, deeply irregularly punctate, punctures near eyes and on the sides of pronotum almost confluent, on the disk of pronotum separated by no more than 1–2 diameters. Pronotum transverse, 1.43–1.52 times as wide as long. Elytra elongate, subparallel, 1.6 times as long as wide, with polygonal microsculpture. Striae deep and very finely punctate. Intervals slightly convex. Claws with 6 teeth. Abdominal sterna with pubescence. Propleuron strongly rugose, mesepisterna slightly punctate, metepisterna slightly transversely rugose. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[863,949,1341,1366]" captionStart="FIGURES 19 – 21" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1796,1819]" captionTargetBox="[161,1424,604,1768]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,589,1776]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 19 – 21. Aedeagus of Singilis (s. str.): 19 — S. ambulans (Peringuey, 1896) (Tshulu, RSA); 20 — S. allardi (Basilewsky, 1963) (Solwezi, Zambia); 21 — S. shavrini sp. n., Holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/265440/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="184">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
). Tip of aedeagus downturned. Internal sac with one group of short spines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
